{{Infobox rockunit | name = Casma Group | image = | caption = | type = [[Group (stratigraphy)|Geological group]] | period = Cenomanian | age = [[Albian]]-[[Cenomanian]] | prilithology = [[Limestone]], [[marl]], [[sandstone]], [[conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]] | otherlithology = [[Gypsum]], [[tuff]] | namedfor = [[Casma]] | namedby = | region = [[Casma Province]], [[Ancash Region]] | country = {{PER}} | coordinates = | unitof = | subunits = | underlies = | overlies = | thickness = | extent = | area = | map = | map_caption = }} The '''Casma Group''' ({{lang-es|Grupo Casma}}) is a [[Group (stratigraphy)|stratigraphic group]] of [[Mesozoic|Mesozoic-aged]] [[sedimentary formation]]s exposed along the coast and within the [[Cordillera Occidental (Peru)|Cordillera Occidental]] near [[Casma]], [[Peru]].
The sediments of the Casma Group reflect deposition in two distinct environments of the West Peruvian Basin. Some sediments were deposited near the [[Casma Volcanic Arc]] in an [[craton|intra-cratonic]] [[sedimentary basin]] that was occasionally connected to the ocean. Other sediments were deposited in what was once a [[continental platform]] bounded by [[reef]]s and with [[Anoxic waters|anoxic pockets]].<ref name=Adlineetal1983>{{cite journal |last=Compare |first=Dominique |last2=Adline |first2=Ghilaine |last3=Romani |first3=Maurice |last4=Angeles |first4=Carlos |date=1983 |title=Contribución al estudio de las formaciones volcánicas y sedimentarias del Grupo Casma en la transversal del río Huara, Cuenca oeste-peruana |url=http://www.ifeanet.org/publicaciones/boletines/12%281-2%29/75.pdf |journal=Bulletin de l'Institut français d'études andines |publisher= |volume=XII |issue=1–2 |pages=75–89 |doi= |access-date=30 December 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref>
Together with the [[Morro Solar Group|Morro Solar]] and [[Imperial Group (geology)|Imperial Group]]s, the Casma Group contains [[Clastic rock|clastic]] [[Volcano-sedimentary sequence|volcanosedimentary]] material derivative of the Mesozoic [[Casma Volcanic Arc]].<ref name=PfeiffGonz2013>{{cite journal |last=Pfiffner |first=Adrian O. |last2=Gonzalez |first2=Laura |date=2013 |title=Mesozoic–Cenozoic Evolution of the Western Margin of South America: Case Study of the Peruvian Andes |url= |journal=Geoscience |publisher= |volume=3 |issue= |pages=262–310 |doi=10.3390/geosciences3020262 }}</ref> The [[fold (geology)|fold]]ing of the Casma Group sediments is the result of the Cretaceous [[Andean orogeny#Northern Peru (3–13° S)|Mochica Phase]] of the [[Andean orogeny]].<ref name=PfeiffGonz2013/> The group is [[intrusion (geology)|intruded]] by [[pluton]]s of the [[Coastal Batholith of Peru]].<ref name=PfeiffGonz2013/>
The Casma Group include the following lithologies: [[gypsum]], [[limestone]], [[marl]], [[tuff]], [[lava flow]]s, [[sandstone]] and [[conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]].<ref name=Adlineetal1983/>
