The '''Colangüil Batholith''' is a group of [[pluton]]s in western [[Argentina]] between the latitudes of 29 and 31° S.<ref name=LLambiasSato1990/> The plutons of the batholith were [[Methods of pluton emplacement|emplaced]] and cooled in the [[Paleozoic|Late Paleozoic]] and the [[Triassic]]. Runs in a north-south direction. The plutons of the batholith are intruded into [[volcanic rock]]s produced by the same plutons plus some earlier deformed basement. The most common rocks in the batholith are [[granodiorite]], [[granite]] and [[leucogranite]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Yoshinobu |first=Aaron S. |last2=Fowler Jr |first2=T. Kenneth |last3=Paterson |first3=Scott R.|last4=Llambias |first4=Eduardo |last5=Tickyj |first5=Hugo |last6=Sato |first6=Ana Maria|date=2003 |title=A view from the roof: magmatic stoping in the shallow crust, Chita pluton, Argentina |journal=[[Journal of Structural Geology]] |publisher= |volume=25 |issue= |pages=1037–1048 |doi= }}</ref> The batholith contains also a [[dyke swarm]] of north-south trending dykes. Compared to other subduction-related batholiths around the [[Pacific Ocean]] Colangüil Batholith is more [[felsic]].<ref name=LLambiasSato1990>{{cite journal |last=Llambias |first=Eduardo Jorge |last2=Ana María |first2=Sato |date=1990 |title=El batolito de Colangüil (29-31°S) Cordillera Frontal de Argentina: Estructura y marco tectónico |url=http://www.andeangeology.equipu.cl/index.php/revista1/article/viewFile/V17n1-a04/pdf |journal=[[Andean Geology|Revista geológica de Chile]] |publisher= |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=89–108 |doi= |access-date=30 August 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref>
Together with the [[Coastal Batholith of central Chile|Chilean Coastal Batholith]] and the [[Elqui-Limarí Batholith]] the Colangüil Batholith is a remnant of the [[volcanic arc]]s that erupted the volcanic material of the [[Choiyoi Group]].<ref name=KleimanJapas2009>{{cite journal |last=Kleiman |first=Laura E. |last2=Japas |first2=María S. |date=2009 |title=The Choiyoi volcanic province at 34°S–36°S (San Rafael, Mendoza, Argentina): Implications for the Late Palaeozoic evolution of the southwestern margin of Gondwana |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Laura_Kleiman/publication/241406241_The_Choiyoi_volcanic_province_at_34S-36S_%28San_Rafael_Mendoza_Argentina%29_Implications_for_the_Late_Palaeozoic_evolution_of_the_southwestern_margin_of_Gondwana/links/546b47370cf2f5eb18091754.pdf |journal=[[Tectonophysics (journal)|Tectonophysics]] |publisher= |volume=473 |issue= |pages=283–299 |doi= |access-date=5 January 2016}}</ref>
The batholith is made up six major units:<ref name=LLambiasSato1990/> *Granodiorita Las Piedritas (made up by five plutons) *Granito Los Puentes (made up by three plutons) *Granito Las Opeñas (made up by a single pluton) *Granito Agua Blanca (made up by two plutons) *Granito Los Lavaderos (made up by a single pluton) *Riolita Tres Quebradas ([[subvolcanic rock|subvolcanic]] intrusions)
