[[Image:Communitive midshaft humeral fracture callus.jpg|thumb|[[Bone fracture|Comminuted]] midshaft [[humerus fracture]] with '''callus formation'''.]] A '''fibrocartilage callus''' is a temporary formation of [[fibroblast]]s and [[chondroblast]]s which forms at the area of a [[bone fracture]] as the [[bone]] attempts to [[healing|heal]] itself. The cells eventually dissipate and become dormant, lying in the resulting [[extracellular matrix]] that is the new bone. The callus is the first sign of union visible on x-rays, usually 3 weeks after the fracture. Callus formation is slower in adults than in children, and in [[cortical bone]]s than in [[cancellous bone]]s.
