'''Hun Kal''' is a small [[impact crater|crater]] on [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] that serves as the reference point for the planet's system of [[longitude]]. The longitude of Hun Kal's center is defined as being 20° W, thus establishing the planet's [[prime meridian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://astrogeology.usgs.gov/Projects/WGCCRE/constants/iau2000_table1.html|accessdate=22 October 2009|title=USGS Astrogeology: Rotation and pole position for the Sun and planets (IAU WGCCRE)}}</ref>
[[Image:Hun Kal crater on Mercury.jpg|thumb|left|150px|This image shows the surrounding context of Hun Kal, which is almost invisibly tiny near the center.]]
Hun Kal was chosen as a reference point since the actual prime meridian was in shadow when ''[[Mariner 10]]'' photographed the region, hiding any features near 0° longitude from view.

Hun Kal is about 1.5&nbsp;km in diameter.<ref>{{gpn|62753|Hun Kal}}</ref>

The name "Hun Kal" means '20' in the [[Mayan languages|language of the Maya]].
