{{Infobox book | name = The Second Stage | image = The Second Stage (Friedan book).jpg | alt = Cover | caption = | author = [[Betty Friedan]] | subject = [[Feminism]] | genre = | publisher = Summit Books | pub_date = 1981 | media_type = | pages = 344 | awards = | isbn = 978-0-671-41034-6 | oclc = 7717510 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Second Stage''''' is a 1981 book by American [[feminist]], [[activist]] and [[writer]] [[Betty Friedan]], best known for her earlier book ''[[The Feminine Mystique]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Interviews with Betty Friedan|year=2003|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|location=Jackson, Miss.|isbn=978-1-57806-480-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JXYStj1VHSoC&lpg=PA53&dq=%22Second%20Stage%22%20friedan&pg=PA53#v=onepage&q&f=false|editor=Sherman, Janann|page=53}}</ref>
==Summary== Friedan contends that "first stage" of feminism, a movement intended to liberate women from their traditional role as only mothers and house-wives, was coming to an end with the deadline for the ratification of The [[Equal Rights Amendment]], and that it was time to take feminism to a new stage, which could better deal with the issues of a new generation of women.<ref>{{cite news|last=Robertson|first=Nan|title=Betty Friedan Ushers in a 'Second Stage'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/99/05/09/specials/friedan-stage.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 19, 1981}}</ref>
Issues discussed include: the double enslavement of women at work and at home, the [[social evolution]] of [[masculinity]], political [[backlash (sociology)|backlash]] to [[feminist]] [[lobbying]], developments in the field of [[management]] and leadership, and the need to recognize the social and economic value of traditional female occupations.
